	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>‘Fishing-vessel monitoring systems: past, present and future’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> On November 25th, the OECD ‘High Seas Task Force’ published a study entitled ‘Fishing vessel monitoring systems: past, present and future’ which highlights both the potential use and the problems associated with the use of VMS.</p><p> On the positive side, the efficiency of protection and compliance activities has improved, as the authorities can now accurately follow, in near real time, the positions of all licensed fishing vessels. Furthermore, timely access to the positions of all licensed vessels provides a considerable advantage in the detection of non-licensed vessels.</p><p> Problems highlighted in the study include the fact that, ‘in most VMS systems the vessel operator is permitted to select the specific equipment that will be used from a range of commercially available models ... this is particularly true of distant-water vessels that participate in VMS systems ... Few coastal states that welcome foreign vessels have the political clout to impose stringent requirements as to VMS equipment’. It then states that: ‘It is not difficult to imagine, in such a context, that an operator who participates in illegal fishing activities could conspire to corrupt VMS data so as to mislead the authorities by, in the first instance, choosing equipment which he deems most vulnerable to modification for this purpose’.</p><p> The study concludes that ‘VMS can provide valuable assistance in solving IUU fishing problems, but success will be the result of rigorous planning and application of monitoring control and surveillance schemes and fisheries management plans into which VMS makes a valuable contribution.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>High Seas Task Force </i>website - ‘Fishing vessel monitoring systems: past, present and future’</p><p>

<a href="http://www.high-seas.org/docs/hstf_vms_final1.pdf" target="_self">http://www.high-seas.org/docs/hstf_vms_final1.pdf</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In many quarters VMS is being hailed as ‘the’ answer to many of the problems besetting MCS systems. This study is important in highlighting both the strengths and weaknesses of VMS, and in questioning popular myths about its fool-proof nature.</p><p> There is also a general need for MCS programmes to include significant components on local human resource and infrastructure development, including the training of inspectors.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

